Patch Set 1:

I was looking into a test for this, was thinking we could compare the major version from glance.version.version_info to the first character of glance.db.migration.CURRENT_RELEASE (do we know what's going to happen after the 'z' release? do we start at 'a' again?), but pbr is still reporting master's major version as 17.  I guess that won't change until we do a release from master.  I wonder if we should do a scratch release or something after the stable branch is cut?  Maybe Sean or Doug will have an idea.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

PBR should be giving a higher version number after this had merged:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/610560/

There is some description of the mechanics of that patch here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2018-October/135706.html

Patch Set 1:

I put up a test: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/632517/ based on this patch.  I think it shows that pbr still thinks master is at 17 (or it may show that I don't know how to use pbr correctly).

Patch Set 1:

> I put up a test: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/632517/ based on
 > this patch.  I think it shows that pbr still thinks master is at 17
 > (or it may show that I don't know how to use pbr correctly).

I get 17.1.0 instead of 17.0.0 when I run "python setup.py --version" on glance master, which is what I would expect with the pbr instruction to increment the version number for a feature. To get to 18 you'll have to create a patch similar to Sean's that uses the pbr instruction to indicate there is a breaking change.

Patch Set 1:

... and I just noticed that Doug already pointed this out!

Patch Set 1:

> Is there any reason *not* to have the major version incremented in
 > master as soon as master opens for development (i.e., after the
 > stable branch is cut at RC-time)?

Not all repos would want to bump up the major version right away, so that is not done be default. In most cases, the version number just needs to be higher to allow upgrading from the last full release, so a feature bump is sufficient for that.

If that does not work for our case here, then in that case you can do a major bump.

Patch Set 1:

OK, here's what I think we need to do timing-wise:
1 - merge https://review.openstack.org/#/c/632517/ (adds the test to make sure pbr and the alembic migration constant are in sync)
2 - merge https://review.openstack.org/#/c/633011/ (beta release of glance, will make release version==18 , which should cause (1) to fail and wedge the gate
3 - merge this change (which will correct the alembic migration constant and restore glance tests to passing)

Patch Set 1:

Looks reasonable to me. I can't really judge though if it's a complte fix.

Even if the code itself doesn't require/follow depends-on with releases, I think it's clearer and 'more automatic' if we added a Depends-On here.

NOTE: The emergency fallback (in case this patch doesn't fix the failing glance unit tests once the beta is released) will be to revert https://review.openstack.org/#/c/632517/
